"§1"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `edgeCount G`
#: Game.Levels.GraphTheory.L03_Handshake
msgid "§0 gives you the number of edges in graph G."
msgstr ""

#. §0: ```
#. sumDegrees_addEdge (G : Graph) (e : Edge) (h : e ∉ G.E) : sumDegrees (addEdge G e)  = sumDegrees G + 2
#. ```
#. §1: `rw [sumDegrees_addEdge]`
#. §2: `e ∉ G.E`
#. §3: `sumDegrees_addEdge`
#. §4: `h : e ∉ G.E`
#. §5: `rw [sumDegrees_addEdge G e h]`
#. §6: `e ∉ G.E`
#: Game.Levels.GraphTheory.L02_AddEdge
msgid "§0\n"
"Adding one new edge increases the total degree sum by 2.\n"
"\n"
"## Important:\n"
"Doing just §1 forces you to prove §2 later as that assumption is an argument\n"
"for §3. If you already have §4 as a hypothesis, you can directly try\n"
"§5. Providing all the arguments here means you don't have prove\n"
"separately §6 later."
msgstr ""

#. §0: ```
#. -- if the sum of a sequence of numbers is even, the number of odd numbers in the sequence must be even
#. axiom even_sum_even_odds (A : Multiset Nat) (hA : Even (A.sum)) : Even (A.filter (fun a => Odd a)).card
#. ```
#. §1: `even_sum_even_odds A hA`
#. §2: `A`
#. §3: `∑ (a ∈ A)`
#. §4: `A`
#. §5: `hA`
#: Game.Levels.GraphTheory.L04_OddDegVerts
msgid "§0\n"
"§1 is the proof that the total number of odd numbers in §2 must be even if\n"
"§3 is even.  The hypothesis that the sum of the elements of §4 is even is §5."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `Bipartite G`
#. §1: ```
#. def Bipartite (G : Graph) : Prop :=
#.   ∃ c, ValidColoring G c
#. ```
#. §2: `ValidColoring`
#. §3: `Color`
#. §4: `rw [Bipartite]`
#: Game.Levels.GraphTheory.L07_Bipartite
msgid "§0 is the proposition that a graph is two-colourable, i.e.\n"
"§1\n"
"See the definition of §2 and §3 for more. Use §4 to expand this definition."
msgstr ""

#: Game.Levels.AlgebraWorld
msgid "Algebra World"
msgstr ""

#. §0: ```
#. def ValidColoring
#.   (G : Graph)
#.   (c : Nat → Color) : Prop :=
#.   ∀ e ∈ G.E, c e.fst ≠ c e.snd
#. ```
#. §1: `G`
#. §2: `rw [ValidColoring]`
#: Game.Levels.GraphTheory.L05_TwoColour
msgid "§0\n"
"A valid colouring of a graph §1 is one where each node is assigned some colour such that no two\n"
"adjacent nodes have the same colour. Use §2 to expand its definition in your proofs."
msgstr ""
